<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Introduction to HTML File Format</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            line-height: 1.6;
            margin: 20px;
            background-color: #f4f4f4;
        }
        h1 {
            color: #333;
        }
        p {
            color: #555;
        }
        code {
            background-color: #eee;
            padding: 2px 4px;
            border-radius: 4px;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Introduction to HTML File Format</h1>
    <p>
        HTML, or Hypertext Markup Language, is the standard markup language used for creating web pages and web applications. It provides the basic structure of sites, which is enhanced and modified by other technologies such as CSS (Cascading Style Sheets) and JavaScript. 
    </p>
    <p>
        An HTML file is essentially a text file, with the extension <code>.html</code> or <code>.htm</code>, that contains a series of elements and tags to define the content and layout of a webpage. Each HTML tag serves a specific purpose, such as creating headings, paragraphs, links, images, and lists, making it integral to the web development process.
    </p>
    <p>
        HTML is constantly evolving, with the current official version being HTML5, which introduces new features and capabilities aimed at improving multimedia support, semantic structure, and device compatibility. Understanding the HTML file format is fundamental for anyone venturing into web design and development.
    </p>
</body>
</html>
```

