\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{graphicx}

\title{Introduction to the TEX File Format}
\author{Your Name}
\date{\today}

\begin{document}
\maketitle

\section{Introduction}

The \TeX\ file format, created by Donald Knuth in the late 1970s, is a typesetting system widely used for producing high-quality documents that require complex formatting, including those with intricate mathematical expressions. As a powerful tool for technical and scientific documentation, \TeX\ is favored by researchers, mathematicians, and professionals in various fields due to its precise control over typographic layout.

\TeX\ files are primarily written in plain text and usually have the extension `.tex`. The format supports a comprehensive set of commands and macros, allowing users to define their own styles and structures for documents. Fundamental features of \TeX\ include the ability to manage bibliographies, create tables of contents, and incorporate graphics seamlessly into the text.

In addition to the core \TeX\ language, various macro packages exist, such as LaTeX, which extend its capabilities and provide a more user-friendly interface for document creation. These packages simplify tasks such as styling, referencing, and structuring documents while maintaining the high-quality output for which \TeX\ is known.

This document aims to provide an overview of the \TeX\ file format, highlighting its features, common usage scenarios, and the advantages it offers for academic and professional documentation.

\end{document}
```

